<br>
I havent written on here in a while, and very few people know me (hi Rombus)  Anyway, What sony has done is actually work on one of their core design flaws. Grouping, in a group-based game.  For the past years, soloing and &quot;2-boxing&quot; have become the way of the power gamer.  It has been very beneficial for people to gain solo experience over that of a group.  Why split experience 6 ways, when you can mooch all that to yourself!  Anyway, I believe they are going about it wrong though.  Here are my thoughts!  <br>
<br>
They want to raise the benefits of grouping, yet allow people who are not of the mold &quot;slower/MT/healer&quot; to contribute to the group and actually be wanted in these groups!  So to fix this, it appears they give additonal benefits to having Full 6-man groups and decreasing solo experience given. <br>
<br>
  Why must they only look in this route to give benefits?<br>
<br>
My thought to fix these situations are:<br>
<br>
-Give bonus experience modifiers when mobs are killed within a certain time limit.  This would be a bonus to any group to have a few extra damage dealers (rangers/rogues/wizards)<br>
<br>
-Give bonus experience modifiers when mobs lose X percentage of their life due to DoT's.  <br>
<br>
These are only two that I just thought up off the top of my head here writing this article.  Obviously you could make bonus modifiers given for any criteria for any class not warranted for heavy grouping.  <br>
<br>
The scenario could be a &quot;hey, grab that paladin, you get a sweet exp bonus with 2hand slashing on these mobs&quot;  <br>
<br>
Anyway, you see my point.  This is where the changes need to be addressed, rather than just general grouping experience modifier changes. Any thoughts about this?<br>
<br>
Sage Xarek<br>
Retired Arcanist of Triton<br>
